Date: October 1994.  
Abstract: In this paper information modelling is considered as a process leading to a grammar that describes the communication of an information system with its users. This grammar (the information grammar) should approximate as close as possible the language spoken in the problem domain (the expert language). We first describe how the information grammar is constructed and its relation to the expert language. The information grammar is centered around the information structure and concretized by names for the elements of the information structure and verbalization rules for their instances. PSM is used to describe an information structure, while LISA-D is the framework for the information grammar. The semantics of LISA-D is expressed in terms of path expressions, a (for this purpose) convenient variant of relational algebra. As it is important that queries can be formulated in a way close to the perception of users, LISA-D exploits the natural language approach of NIAM (of which PSM is an extension). Queries in LISA-D can be formulated in terms used in the application domain involved. This, of course, is an important prerequisite for achieving succesful query formulation support. Finally, the concepts of query by navigation and query by construction are introduced as mechanisms to support query formulation.
